alternatives.transcript: mister palmer is a sixty two year old male presenting with a chief complaint of shortness of breath and fatigue mister palmer states that a couple of weeks ago he was walking with his friends and had shortness of breath palpitations wheezing lightheadedness and feelings of painting that continue to occur when exercising he states symptoms go away at rest patient has history of hypertension for which he takes lisinopril ten milligrams every day and family history of sudden death with his mother and his father had a heart attack at sixty nine years old patient also has history of cardiac catheterization but no other surgeries or procedures patient vitals were normal with oxygen of ninety six percent and respiratory rate of sixteen except for elevated heart rate at one hundred ten beats per minute and blood pressure of one thirty over ninety patient is a math teacher living with his husband and follows a balanced diet with a cup of coffee a day and does not drink or smoke patient is unable to exercise due to symptoms patient had fatigue wheezing presyncope but no chest muscle or joint pain patient does not have orthopnea fever chills weight changes gait changes headaches stiffness dysphasia confusion dizziness vision changes or hearing loss patient's physical exam showed pmi displaced laterally no chest wall tenderness positive jugular vein distension rails wheezing no cough regular rate no regurg murmurs or gallops patient had positive pedal pulses and pedal edema and nontender cap patient's osteopathic screening exam displayed no chart changes and no chapman points were tender patient's chest x-ray showed cardiomegaly ekg displayed sinus rhythm normal axis left ventricular voltage criteria tall r wave and septal leads echo showed hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with left ventricle asymmetric in and increased intervention intraventricular septum hypertrophy and injection fraction of sixty percent labs of troponin and bnp were within normal limits patient was informed of his diagnosis of familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in new york heart association class two heart failure and informed of admission to telemetry discontinuation of lisinopril starting of disopuramide one hundred milligrams patient was referred to interventional cardiology for aicd placement and cardiac surgeon for septomyectomy and alcohol injection patient is to exercise as tolerated follow regular diet have oxygen cannula maintain oxygen above ninety six percent given dvt prophylaxis use daily weight strict input output and vitals checked every two hours patient had no additional questions and has support from husband okay
